# Pipeline Module

## Responsibility

The `pipeline` module defines the orchestration boundary of the MLOps system.

It is responsible for:
- Acting as the single CLI entrypoint to the system
- Parsing command-line arguments
- Loading and validating configuration
- Initializing logging
- Executing pipeline stages defined in configuration
- Generating a traceable run report after each execution

It is NOT responsible for:
- Model training logic
- Evaluation logic
- Drift detection logic
- Deployment logic
- Registry or lifecycle logic

All business logic is delegated to dedicated modules.

---

## Current Scope

At this stage, the pipeline:
- Parses CLI arguments
- Loads and validates the configuration
- Sets up logging
- Ingests, versions, validates, and splits the dataset
- Runs configured `pipeline_stages` in order with START/END markers
- Stops execution on first stage failure (fail-fast)
- Writes `run_report.json` to the configured `output_dir` after every run (success or failure)
- Exits with code 0 (success) or 1 (failure)

All six stages (`preprocessing`, `training`, `evaluation`, `model_analysis`,
`promotion`, `deployment`) are implemented. See the stage table below for what
each one does.

---

## Files

### `run_pipeline.py`

Main CLI entrypoint. Coordinates the full pipeline execution flow.

Responsibilities:
- Parse `--config` argument
- Resolve config path
- Call `load_config()` from `config.loader`
- Handle validation and YAML errors
- Initialize logging
- Compute config hash via `report.compute_config_hash()`
- Iterate `config.pipeline_stages` and call `steps.execute_stage()` per stage
- Collect `StageResult` objects and abort on first failure
- Build and write run report via `report.build_run_report()` and `report.write_run_report()`
- Exit with appropriate code based on stage outcomes

Design principles:
- Must remain thin ‚Äî coordinates, does not contain business logic
- Delegates stage execution to `steps.py`
- Delegates report generation to `report.py`
- Unpacks `PipelineConfig` into primitive values before passing to report module

Registered via:
`pyproject.toml` ‚Üí `[project.scripts]`

---

### `steps.py`

Pipeline stage execution with structured logging and timing.

Responsibilities:
- Define `StageResult` dataclass capturing stage name, status, timestamps, duration, and error
- Maintain `_STAGE_REGISTRY` mapping stage names to callable functions
- Execute individual stages via `execute_stage()` with START/END log markers
- Catch and record stage failures without crashing the pipeline
- Return a `StageResult` for every execution attempt (success or failure)

Design principles:
- Registry-based dispatch ‚Äî new stages are added by changing a dict value, not by modifying `execute_stage()`
- START/END markers are always paired, even on failure
- `KeyError` for unknown stages propagates (programming error), all other exceptions are caught and recorded
- `StageResult` is a dataclass (not frozen) because it is built incrementally during execution

Registered stages:

| Stage             | Function                  | Status                                                                 |
|---|---|---|
| `preprocessing`   | `_preprocessing_stage`    | Implemented ‚Äî delegates to `src.data.preprocess`                       |
| `training`        | `_training_stage`         | Implemented ‚Äî delegates to `src.training.<task>.train.run_training`    |
| `evaluation`      | `_evaluation_stage`       | Implemented ‚Äî delegates to `src.evaluation.evaluate`                   |
| `model_analysis`  | `_model_analysis_stage`   | Implemented ‚Äî image-pipeline robustness / ISP sensitivity              |
| `promotion`       | `_promotion_stage`        | Implemented ‚Äî runs promotion rules + approval gate                     |
| `deployment`      | `_deployment_stage`       | Implemented ‚Äî emits deterministic `outputs/deployment_manifest.json`   |

Extension point (e.g. adding a canary or image-build stage on top of the
manifest):
```python
_STAGE_REGISTRY["canary"] = _canary_stage
```

---

### `report.py`

Run report generation and persistence.

Responsibilities:
- Compute a deterministic SHA-256 hash of the raw config file (`compute_config_hash()`)
- Build the run report dict from primitive values and stage results (`build_run_report()`)
- Write `run_report.json` to the output directory (`write_run_report()`)

Design principles:
- `build_run_report()` is a pure function ‚Äî no I/O, no logging, no side effects, easily unit-tested
- `write_run_report()` is the single I/O boundary ‚Äî creates directories, writes JSON, logs the path
- Takes primitive arguments (strings, ints), not `PipelineConfig` ‚Äî loose coupling to config module
- Uses `dataclasses.asdict()` to convert `StageResult` objects ‚Äî automatically captures new fields

Report schema (`run_report.json`):
```json
{
    "project_id": "lightweight-mlops-pipeline-v0.1.0",
    "config_hash": "sha256:...",
    "timestamp": "2026-02-20T14:30:00.123456+00:00",
    "task_type": "classification",
    "random_seed": 42,
    "executed_stages": [
        {
            "stage": "training",
            "status": "completed",
            "started_at": "...",
            "ended_at": "...",
            "duration_seconds": 0.001,
            "error": null
        }
    ],
    "overall_status": "completed"
}
```

---

## Module Dependencies

```
run_pipeline.py
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ src.config.loader    (load_config, PipelineConfig)
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ src.pipeline.steps   (execute_stage, StageResult)
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ src.pipeline.report  (compute_config_hash, build_run_report, write_run_report)

steps.py
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ src.config.loader    (PipelineConfig ‚Äî type hint only)
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ src.data.preprocess  (run_preprocessing ‚Äî called by _preprocessing_stage)

report.py
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ src.pipeline.steps   (StageResult ‚Äî type only, used with asdict())
```

All dependencies are one-directional. No circular imports.